For example, the following fails since only 4 containers are found instead of 6.

```java
class TestKitTests {

	@Test
	void executeTests() {
		EngineExecutionResults results = EngineTestKit.engine("junit-jupiter")//
				.selectors(selectClass(MainTest.class))//
				.execute();

		results.allEvents().debug(System.out);
		results.containerEvents().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(6));
		results.testEvents().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(2));
	}

}
```

FWIW, it doesn't matter that the parent class is `abstract`. The test kit test fails in the same manner with the following.

```java
	static class AbstractClassWithNestedTest {

		String expectedValue() {
			return "foo";
		}

		@Nested
		class AbstractNested {

			@Test
			void abstractClassAssert1() {
				Assertions.assertEquals(expectedValue(), "pass");
			}
		}
	}
```

@marcphilipp, here's everything in one "source file" to simplify matters.

```java
import static org.junit.platform.engine.discovery.DiscoverySelectors.selectClass;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Nested;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.platform.testkit.engine.EngineExecutionResults;
import org.junit.platform.testkit.engine.EngineTestKit;

public class MainTest {

	@Nested
	class Inner1 extends AbstractClassWithNestedTest {

		@Override
		String expectedValue() {
			return "pass";
		}
	}

	@Nested
	class Inner2 extends AbstractClassWithNestedTest {

		@Override
		String expectedValue() {
			return "fail";
		}
	}

	static abstract class AbstractClassWithNestedTest {

		abstract String expectedValue();

		@Nested
		class AbstractNested {

			@Test
			void abstractClassAssert1() {
				Assertions.assertEquals(expectedValue(), "pass");
			}
		}
	}

	static class TestKitTests {

		@Test
		void executeTests() {
			EngineExecutionResults results = EngineTestKit.engine("junit-jupiter")//
					.selectors(selectClass(MainTest.class))//
					.execute();

			results.allEvents().debug(System.out);
			results.containerEvents().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(6));
			results.testEvents().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(2));
		}

	}
}
```

**Update**: this passes against the `5.4.x` branch, so it's a regression in 5.5.

```java
	static class TestKitTests {

		@Test
		void executeTests() {
			EngineExecutionResults results = EngineTestKit.engine("junit-jupiter")//
					.selectors(selectClass(MainTest.class))//
					.execute();

			results.all().debug(System.out);
			results.containers().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(6));
			results.tests().assertStatistics(stats -> stats.started(2));
		}

	}
```

Using _old_ test kit event filter method names.
